Cape Town - A Metrorail commuter train has caught fire at the Cape Town station with smoke in the air visible as far as Milnerton. Emergency services say that the cause of the fire is yet to be determined with no injuries or casualties. City of Cape Town fire and rescue spokesperson Theo Layne said that the train caught alight at around 3:45pm with emergency services on the scene immediately. “We had four fire engines and two water tankers currently on the scene fighting the blaze. The fire was contained with 11 carriages destroyed as well as railway infrastructure,” he said.   To view this video please enable JavaScript, and consider upgrading to a web browser that
    supports HTML5 video This is a modal window. Beginning of dialog window. Escape will cancel and close the window. End of dialog window. While emergency services were extinguishing the fire entrance to the station for commuters was limited by security with and train lines momentarily disrupted. Once the fire was extinguished most of the service resumed as normal with minor delays. Over the past month, there have been at least four arson attacks on trains with one reported death due to those attacks. Damages to Metrorail infrastructure has amounted to R19 million over this period. Concerned Capetonians began posting videos and pictures to social media after initially seeing the massive cloud of smoke over the station but by 4:15 pm the smoke had all gone. 